ce:section.ce:para:
To corroborate the analytical performance of the designed aptasensor in RAC detection, different concentrations of the RAC were incubated onto the aptasensor surface for 60 min and the Nyquist curves were recorded (Fig. 4
                        ). Based on Fig. 4, the increase of the RAC concentration leads to more formation of the RAC/Apt complexes onto the aptasensor surface. Consequently, more blocking of the electron transfer reaction of the redox probe on the sensing surface is resulted. Thus, under the optimized conditions, the Rct value is at a minimum value in the absence of the RAC as the target molecule (gray curve) and this is gradually increased by more addition of the RAC concentration. Accordingly, there is a good correlation between the EIS technique response and the RAC concentration by achieving three good linear relationships curves. Accordingly, for lower concentrations in the range from 1 fM to 1.1 pM an equation of y = 3 × 106 [RAC] + 2088.4 (with correlation coefficient (R2 = 0.995)), for middle concentrations in the range from 1.1 pM to 1.4 nM an equation of y = 1781.5 [RAC] + 5701 (R2 = 0.9942) and for higher concentrations in the range from 1.4 nM to 901.4 nM an equation of y = 4.8284 [RAC] + 8432.7 (R2 = 0.9905) were founded. Based on S/N = 3, a detection limit (LOD) down to 330 aM was calculated. By comparison of the obtained results with other reported RAC sensors in Table 1
                        , it can be concluded that the obtained analytical characteristics such as the LOD value and the linear range domain are superior of the other reported sensors. These satisfactory results may be attributed to some important reasons: (1) presence of the QDs@GQDs nanolayer which is presented a synergistic effect of unique features of the electron transfer tunneling and increasing of the surface area, making more site for high density of the AgNPs on the modified GCE surface; (2) adding AgNPs as a linker on the QDs@GQDs surface and the formation of a self-assembled monolayer of the AgNPs via thiol groups in the nanolayer; (3) utilizing Apt sequence with inherent advantages as the RAC capture for more selective sensing of the target; (4) more loading of the Apt sequence as the RAC capture via the formation of the favored Ag-NH2 bonds related to the amine groups of the Apt and the AgNPs onto the AgNPs/QDs@GQDs/GCE surface to embed an admirable sensing interface; (5) using ferro/ferricyanide as a universal small probe redox in an applicable potential range of −0.2 to 0.7. Besides, the synthesis of the AgNPs and the GQDs under a simple, fast and economical process as other advantages of this strategy can help to construct the aptasensor with lower costs.
